A large deviation from this expected value is not itself evidence of partisan gerrymandering because differences could be caused by any number of factors, but it can be combined with the lopsided wins test and the mean-median difference to estimate the effects of a possible partisan gerrymander. In TN in 2016, Democrats won 14 out of 63 seats with 37.4% of the statewide vote. Our simulations indicate that, according to nationwide trends in 2016, Democrats would be expected to win 33.149 seats.

The difference of 19.149 is inconsistent with nationwide trends, and suggests that TN may have been gerrymandered to gain an advantage for REPUBLICAN.
